  <div class="checklist-disclaimer">
    <p><strong>NON-CONTRACTUAL GUIDANCE</strong></p>
    <p>This checklist is provided as guidance only and does not form part of the tenancy agreement. It summarises key legal obligations for landlords in Northern Ireland under the Private Tenancies Act (NI) 2022 and related legislation. For detailed requirements, consult the relevant legislation or seek professional legal advice.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>1. Landlord Registration (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Registered with the Landlord Registration Scheme</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">All private landlords in Northern Ireland must register with the Landlord Registration Scheme NI before letting a property. Registration must be renewed annually.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Property included in registration</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Each property you let must be included in your landlord registration.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Private Tenancies Act (Northern Ireland) 2022</p>

  <h3>2. Deposit Protection (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Deposit protected within 28 days</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">If you take a deposit, it must be protected in a government-approved scheme within 28 days of receipt. The Tenancy Deposit Scheme NI is the approved scheme.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Prescribed Information provided within 28 days</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">You must provide the tenant with the scheme's Prescribed Information within 28 days. This includes deposit amount, scheme details, and circumstances for deductions.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Tenancy Deposit Schemes Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2012</p>

  <h3>3. Tenancy Information Notice (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Tenancy Information Notice provided at start of tenancy</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">You must give the tenant a completed Tenancy Information Notice at the start of the tenancy. This provides key information about the landlord, property, rent, deposit, and key contacts.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Keep copy for records</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Retain a copy of the notice for your records as proof of compliance.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Private Tenancies Act (Northern Ireland) 2022</p>

  <h3>4. Gas Safety (Mandatory if gas supplied)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Valid Gas Safety Certificate</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A Gas Safe registered engineer must inspect all gas appliances annually. The certificate must be provided to the tenant before they move in.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Copy provided before occupation</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">New tenants must receive a copy before moving in and within 28 days of each annual check.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Gas Safety (Installation and Use) Regulations 1998</p>

  <h3>5. Electrical Safety (From 1 April 2025)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Electrical Installation Condition Report (EICR)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">From 1 April 2025, landlords must have an EICR completed every 5 years by a competent person. The report must show the installation is satisfactory.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Copy provided to tenant</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">New tenants must receive a copy before moving in. Existing tenants within 28 days of inspection.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Portable appliance testing (PAT)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Any electrical appliances provided with the property should be tested and safe.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Private Tenancies Act (Northern Ireland) 2022</p>

  <h3>6. Energy Performance Certificate (EPC)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Valid EPC available</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">An EPC must be made available to prospective tenants free of charge. The EPC is valid for 10 years.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>EPC provided to tenant</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Tenants must receive a copy of the EPC.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Energy Performance of Buildings (Certificates and Inspections) Regulations (NI) 2008</p>

  <h3>7. Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarms</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Working smoke alarm fitted</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">At least one working smoke alarm must be installed in the property. Best practice is one on each storey.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Carbon monoxide alarm where required</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A CO alarm is required in any room with a solid fuel burning appliance. Best practice is to install one near any combustion appliance.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Alarms tested at start of tenancy</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Ensure all alarms are in working order at the start of the tenancy.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Private Tenancies Act (Northern Ireland) 2022</p>

  <h3>8. Fitness for Human Habitation</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Property meets the Fitness Standard</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">The property must meet the statutory fitness standard. This includes: structural stability, freedom from serious disrepair, freedom from dampness, adequate lighting, heating, and ventilation, and satisfactory facilities for food preparation and sanitation.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing (NI) Order 1981, Article 46</p>

  <h3>9. Rent Increase Restrictions</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Understand rent increase rules</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Under the Private Tenancies Act (NI) 2022, rent can only be increased once every 12 months. You must give at least 3 months' written notice of any increase.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>No increase in first 12 months</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">The rent cannot be increased during the first 12 months of the tenancy.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Private Tenancies Act (Northern Ireland) 2022</p>

  <h3>10. HMO Requirements (If applicable)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>HMO registration (if required)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Houses in Multiple Occupation in Northern Ireland must be registered with the local council. HMO registration requirements differ from England/Wales/Scotland.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>HMO management standards met</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">HMOs must meet prescribed management standards including fire safety, maintenance, and cleanliness of common areas.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Houses in Multiple Occupation Act (Northern Ireland) 2016</p>

